# Check the datatype of each columns with the unique values
def checkDataTypeWithUnique(df):
    for col_name in df.columns:
        print(col_name, "=>", df.dtypes[col_name])
        if df.dtypes[col_name] == 'object':
            print(df[col_name].value_counts())
        else:
            print(df[col_name].unique())
        print("- "*50)

Insights¶

  • Most of the fields(gender, Partner, Dependents, PhoneService, MultipleLines, InternetService, OnlineSecurity, OnlineBackup, DeviceProtection, TechSupport, StreamingTV, StreamingMovies, Contract, PaperlessBilling, PaymentMethod) are string datatype with 2 to 4 unique values.

  • MonthlyCharges : float datatype with continuous values
  • TotalCharges: is a string datatype but it contains continuous float values
  • Churn: is our target class, it is a string datatype with 2 unique values
  • It looks like only TotalCharges column has some missing value

# Create a function that will accept a DataFrame as input and return pie-charts for all the appropriate Categorical features.
# Clearly show percentage distribution in the pie-chart.

# Libraries to handle data visualization
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline

# library for confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# lets convert all the object datatype to categorical varisble
for col in churn_data.columns:
    if churn_data[col].dtype == 'object':
        churn_data[col] = pd.Categorical(churn_data[col])

# all the string datatype features converted to categorical
# now lets define the function for pie chart
def makePieChart(df):
    for feature in df.columns:
        if df[feature].dtype.name == 'category':
            feature_values = list(df[feature].value_counts())
            feature_keys = list(df[feature].unique())
            plt.title(feature)
            plt.axis('equal')
            plt.pie(feature_values, labels=feature_keys, autopct='%0.2f%%')
            plt.show();
            print("_"*100)
            print("\n")
            
makePieChart(churn_data)

Question 2.D:¶

In [156]:
# Share insights for Q2.c.

Insights¶

  • Our target variable Churn distributed as almost 1/4th Yes and 3/4th No
  • The gender and Partner columns are almost in 50:50 ratio
  • The Dependents distribution 70:30 ratio
  • Almost 90% customers are not using PhoneService
  • There are 10% users using MultipleLines
  • 22% users not using InternetService, Fiber optic used by 34% and DSL used by 44% users as InternetService
  • Nearly 30% customers availing OnlineSecurity service
  • OnlineBackup service availing 44% users
  • almost 1/3rd customers using DeviceProtection service
  • 29% customets taking TechSupport
  • Nearly 40% customers having StreamingTV and StreamingMovies service
  • In Contract 55% customers have monthly plan and 1 year and 2 years plans are 21% and 24% respectively
  • Nearly 60% customers using PaperlessBilling facility
  • In PaymentMethod Mailed check, Bank transfer (automatic) and Credit card (automatic) are almost equally distributes 22% each and nearly 34% customers pay using Electronic check
